{"title_page": "Phil Cohen (cultural theorist and ethnographer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Phil Cohen\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = PhilpicpmIMG 0219.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                =\n| caption            = Cohen in 2017\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = 1944\n| birth_place        =London \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        =British \n| citizenship        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         =Writer and Cultural Activist \n| period             = \n| known_for          =Sociology of youth culture; impact of urban regeneration on working class culture; theories of racism and identity. Also a high profile leader of squatters rights movement in London (1960-70s). \n| home_town          =\n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             =Jean McNeil, painter \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| awards             = <!--notable national-level awards only-->\n| website            =https://philcohenworks.com/ \n| education          =St Pauls School, Cambridge University, PhD by publication \n| alma_mater         = <!--will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution-->\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = Basil Bernstein; Gregory Bateson; Michail Bakhtin; Bruno Latour\n| era                = \n| discipline         = Sociologist, Ethnographer\n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th-century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions-->\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Phil Cohen''' (born 1944) is a British cultural theorist, urban ethnographer, community activist, educationalist and poet. He was involved in the London underground counter culture scene and gained public notoriety as 'Dr John', a leader in the [[Squatting|squatter's rights]] movement but is now better known for his work on youth culture and the impact of urban regeneration on working class communities, particularly in East London, with a focus of issues of race and popular racism. More recently the scope of his work has widened to includes issues of identity politics, memory and loss, and the future of the Left in Britain Cohen\u2019s academic work is trans-disciplinary and draws on concepts from linguistics and narratology, psycho-analysis and anthropology, cultural history and social phenomenology. He is currently (2020) Emeritus Professor at the Centre for Cultural Studies at the University of East London, a research fellow at the Young Foundation and Research Director of the Livingmaps Network. Cohen is also a member of [[Compass (think tank)|Compass]], a [[Gramscian]] think tank within the Labour Party and is on the editorial board of [[New Formations]]. His work has been translated into French, German, Swedish, Italian, French and Japanese.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://philcohenworks.com/pcowwp/wp-content/uploads/PCCVjan19.final2_.pdf|title=Phil Cohen, CV|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=|website=philcohenworks.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nPhil Cohen was born into a medical family living in Bloomsbury, Central London. He was  educated at St Paul\u2019s School, London, where he studied classics and history and won a scholarship to Cambridge in 1963.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Reading Room Only|publisher=Five Leaves Publications|year=2013|isbn=978-1907869785|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.historyworkshop.org.uk/reading-room-only/|title=Reading Room Only|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2011|website=History Workshop Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1965 Cohen dropped out of university and after a period of travelling, including work on trawlers, he became involved in the London underground counter culture scene.<ref name=\":0\" /> He subsequently became a community and youth worker in London. He was married to the late Pam Brighton, the theatre director in 1970; their son, Ned, was born the following year. He was divorced in 1978 and later married Jean McNeil, the painter in 1987. They adopted a son, Stephen, who died of an alcohol related illness in  2013 at the age of 33.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=In the best interests of the child : culture, identity, and transracial adoption|date=1994|publisher=Free Association Books|others=Gaber, Ivor., Aldridge, Jane.|isbn=1-85343-152-4|location=London|pages=|chapter=Yesterday's Words, Tomorrow's World: from the Racialisation of Adoption to the Politics of Difference|oclc=31918360}}</ref> This event is a central reference point in much of the creative writing Cohen has produced since then.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/a-tribute-in-words-and-pictures-to-ste-thomson/|title=A tribute in words and pictures to Ste Thomson|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2013|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Cohen's grandfather was a Jewish revolutionary from Vitebsk who emigrated to live in Glasgow before the First World War and was the subject of a recent prose poem.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Postcards to Grandad|publisher=Eyeglass Books|year=2019|isbn=978-1-9164719-2-4|location=|pages=}}</ref><br />\n== Youth Culture and the Alternative Society (1965 -78) ==\nWorking as an assistant to the conceptual artist [[John Latham (artist)|John Latham]], Cohen scripted \u2018happenings\u2019 with Latham and [[Jeff Nuttall]] at [[Better Books]], and was involved in the [[Wholly Communion]] Poetry Event and the [[Dialectics of Liberation Congress|Dialectics of Liberation]] conference. He also wrote for the underground paper [[International Times]]. For a time he was associated with the English [[Situationist International|Situationist]] group and its journal King Mob Echo and took an active part in several of its \u2018provocations\u2019. In 1968 he became involved in a squat at the Bell Hotel in Covent Garden out of which the [[London Street Commune]] movement emerged. Mass squats were organised in a number of prominent public buildings in Central London, culminating in the occupation of the Queen Mother\u2019s ex-residence at 144 Piccadilly in 1969 which became known as 'Hippydilly' and made world headline news.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-49607777|title=When hippy squatters took over a Piccadilly mansion|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As one of the leaders of the movement who spoke to the media Cohen's pseudonym \u2018Dr John' featured in newsreel reports and the national press.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/piccadilly-squatters|title=Piccadilly Squatters|last=Path\u00e9|first=British|website=www.britishpathe.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>  British Pathe described the occupiers as 'scroungers and hell raisers' and Dr John 'the hippy squatter\u2019 briefly became an figure of fear in what he later described as a moral panic about the perceived threat that squatting posed to home ownership and private property.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/144-and-all-that-proud-archivist-event/|title=144 And All That Proud Archivist Event - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the closing down of the street commune squats, Cohen worked as a detached youth worker for the Soho Project and then set up Street Aid as a legal advice and self help organisation for homeless young people in Central London, based initially in Soho and then Covent Garden.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> In 1975/6, with a group of fellow Leftists including [[David Robins]], Cohen occupied a derelict pub near Kings Cross and turned it into a radical cultural and education centre for local estate youth. The pub was burned down in mysterious circumstances''. Knuckle Sandwich:growing up in the working class city'' (1978) written by Cohen and Robins\u00a0gives a detailed account of the project and situates it within an analysis of urban working class youth culture.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Robins, David, 1944-2007.|title=Knuckle sandwich : growing up in the working-class city|date=1978|publisher=Penguin|others=Cohen, Philip, 1944-|isbn=0-14-021977-3|location=Harmondsworth|oclc=4958423}}</ref>\n\nThese experiences led Cohen to develop a [[Gramscian]] perspective on post war youth subcultures in Britain spelt out in a working paper published by the Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies (CCCS) in 1972 \u2018Sub-cultural Conflict and Working Class Community\u2019<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Phil.|title=Sub-cultural conflict and working class community|date=1972|publisher=Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies|oclc=809618727}}</ref> subsequently provided the basis for a CCCS book \u2018Resistance through Rituals\u2019 edited by [[Stuart Hall (cultural theorist)|Stuart Hall]] and Tony Jefferson.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Resistance through rituals : youth subcultures in post-war Britain|date=1993|publisher=Routledge|others=Hall, Stuart, 1932-2014., Jefferson, Tony.|isbn=0-415-09916-1|location=London|oclc=31183761}}</ref> The paper has since been translated into eight European languages and become something of a classic. In this text Cohen develops the notion of youth cultures as collective responses to structural shifts in class identity formation, creating distinct sets of imaginary class relations though specific codes of dress, behaviour, music and language. This analysis was initially applied to [[Mods and rockers|Mods]] and [[Skinhead|Skinheads]], in East London and subsequently to [[Beatnik|Beats]] and [[Hippie|Hippies]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In later work this initial focus on the youth question broadened to include issues of inter-generational transmission, coming of age stories and ideas surrounding different life phases.<br />\n\n== Interventions in Vocational and Anti-Racist Education (1979-1992) ==\nIn 1978 Cohen joined the Sociological Research Unit at the University of London's [[UCL Institute of Education|Institute of Education]], run by [[Basil Bernstein]] and [[Michael Young, Baron Young of Dartington|Michael Young]], carrying out two research projects funded by the [[Leverhulme Trust]] into youth cultures and changing school transitions. This led to a series of publications challenging the \u2018[[New Vocationalism|new vocationalism]]\u2018 and the [[Youth Training Scheme|youth training schemes]] then being introduced by the Conservative government under Margaret Thatcher with the aim of inculcating the values of \u2018enterprise culture\u2019.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bates|first=Inge|title=Schooling for the dole? : the new vocationalism|date=1984|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-1-349-17581-9|location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire|pages=|oclc=562631949}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=1982|title=Schooling for the Dole|url=|journal=New Socialist|volume=3|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nMoving to the Post-16 Centre at the Institute, Cohen collaborated with the Cockpit Cultural Studies Centre to produce a series of photographic exhibitions working with early-leavers focusing on their experience of schooling and issues of working class aspiration, gender identity, and ethnicity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|last2=Chappell|date=1983|title=Leavers and the Three 'L's|url=|journal=Schooling and Culture|volume=13|pages=|via=}}</ref> The No Kidding Project, funded by the [[Greater London Council]] (GLC) produced learning materials to support alternative, more critical forms of vocational education.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen, P.|title=Rethinking the Youth Question : Education, Labour and Cultural Studies.|date=2016|publisher=Macmillan Education, Limited|isbn=978-1-349-25390-6|location=London|pages=326+|oclc=1084386849}}</ref>\u00a0<ref>{{Citation|last=Cohen|first=Philip|title=Schooling for the Dole?|chapter=Against the New Vocationalism|date=1984|pages=104\u2013169|publisher=Macmillan Education UK|doi=10.1007/978-1-349-17581-9_4|isbn=978-0-333-36729-2}}</ref> The theoretical framework for this was developed in a number of articles.<ref>{{Citation|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Rethinking the Youth Question|chapter=Teaching Enterprise Culture: Individualism, Vocationalism and the New Right|date=1997|pages=275\u2013325|publisher=Macmillan Education UK|doi=10.1007/978-1-349-25390-6_10|isbn=978-0-333-63148-5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|date=2014-05-12|editor-last=Ainley|editor-first=Patrick|editor2-last=Rainbird|editor2-first=Helen|title=Apprenticeship: Towards a New Paradigm of Learning|doi=10.4324/9781315042091|isbn=9781315042091}}</ref> This critical pedagogy was then further developed in the field of anti-racist education in a series of initiatives, films and teaching resources designed to offer an alternative to moral, symbolic and doctrinaire forms of anti-racism. These included:\n\n* Playgrounds of Prejudice, an ethnographic study of playground cultures in Dockland schools This was supported by a [https://philcohenworks.com/playgrounds-of-prejudice/ film] of the same title analysing a playground fight between an Irish and a Black boy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/playgrounds-of-prejudice/|title=Playgrounds of Prejudice - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n* Ananse meets Spiderwoman, a learning resource pack for primary schools, published by the British Film Institute.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Philip, 1944-|title=Anansi meets spiderwoman : curriculum resources for tackling common-sense racism in pupil cultures|date=1994|publisher=British Film Institute|others=Haddock, Lynda., Southwark (London, England). Education Department., British Film Institute., University of East London. New Ethnicities Unit.|isbn=0-85170-433-6|location=London|oclc=30400135}}</ref>\n* [http://philcohenworks.com/pcowwp/wp-content/uploads/TRICKS-OF-THE-TRADE1.png Anansi Rap Attack]: a poster produced with the Art of Change.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/tricks-of-the-trade-issues-in-multicultural-education/|title=Tricks of the Trade - Issues in MultiCultural Education - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sXXk_kfAgY8 Empires of the Mind], a film produced by the Open University for the course on \u2018Race, Culture, Difference\u2019.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_79YLaLHXyQ Tricks of the Trade]: a project film including an interview with Stuart Hall.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThis teaching material was supported by a number of theoretical texts, including chapters in an Open University course reader<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Race\", culture, and difference|date=1992|publisher=Sage Publications in association with the Open University|others=Donald, James, 1948-, Rattansi, Ali.|isbn=0-8039-8579-7|location=London|oclc=26052615}}</ref>, and in the Blackwell reader in Racial and Ethnic Studies.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A companion to racial and ethnic studies|date=2002|publisher=Blackwell|others=Goldberg, David Theo., Solomos, John.|isbn=0-585-46732-3|location=Malden, Mass.|oclc=53061669}}</ref>\n\nDuring this period Cohen co-edited with Angela McRobbie the Youth Questions series for Macmillan. His own books published in the series included ''Multi-Racist Britain'' (1994)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Multi-racist Britain|date=1988|publisher=Macmillan Education|others=Cohen, Philip, 1944-, Bains, Harwant S.|isbn=0-333-33249-0|location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire|oclc=18781086}}</ref> and ''Rethinking the Youth Question: education, labour and cultural studies'' (1997)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, P.|title=Rethinking the Youth Question : Education, Labour and Cultural Studies.|date=2016|publisher=Macmillan Education, Limited|isbn=978-1-349-25390-6|oclc=1084386849}}</ref>, which brought together all his academic research on youth culture and schooling.   \n== From Race to Regeneration (1992-2012) ==\nCohen moved to the University of East London (UEL) in 1992 to set up and direct the Centre for New Ethnicities Research (CNER). The centre embarked on a programme of research and community engagement in East London around issues of popular racism and cultural identity. This included curating ''Rich Mix'' (2001), an exhibition of multicultural art in Tower Hamlets and a major conference ''Front Lines, Backyards'' (1998)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Frontlines - backyards.|date=1998|publisher=Lawrence & Wishart|isbn=0-85315-858-4|location=London|oclc=230179182}}</ref> which explored issues surrounding changing identifications people might make when confronted by when confronted by rapid social and demographic change. Research projects included ethnographic studies of frontline situations of racial conflict in East London, a funded research programme on young people\u2019s perceptions of class, gender and ethnicity in two areas of London and Hamburg whose results were published as ''Finding the Way Home'' (2004);<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=R\u00e4thzel, Nora, Hrsg. Cohen, Phil.|title=Finding the way home : young people's stories of gender, ethnicity, class, and places in Hamburg and London|date=2008|publisher=V & R Unipress|isbn=978-3-89971-433-3|oclc=246627976}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title='All White on the Night' in Rising in the East?: the regeneration of East London|last2=Rustin|first2=Mike|date=1996|publisher=Lawrence & Wishart|isbn=0-85315-844-4|editor-last=Butler|editor-first=Tim|location=|pages=|oclc=468564617}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=1997|editor-last=Frankenberg|editor-first=Ruth|title='Labouring Under Whiteness' in Displacing Whiteness|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1215/9780822382270|isbn=978-0-8223-2011-1}}</ref> The centre organised a programme of talks and working papers, some of which was published in ''New Ethnicities, Old Racisms.''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Phil, 1944-|title=New ethnicities, old racisms?|date=1999|publisher=Zed|isbn=1-85649-651-1|oclc=464583221}}</ref> The Centre\u2019s work was influential, especially in directing attention \u00a0to the deeper, more unconscious, reaches of the popular racist imagination. However the use of psychoanalytic and anthropological concepts to understand the interplay of myth, ritual and phantasy in the construction of 'common sense' racist narratives was controversial, especially amongst Marxist critics who took this work to be symptomatic of [[false consciousness]] and an issue of ''Race and Class'' was devoted to attacking the Centre\u2019s work.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Gordon|first=Paul|date=April 2001|title=Psychoanalysis and Racism: The Politics of Defeat|journal=Race & Class|volume=42|issue=4|pages=17\u201334|doi=10.1177/0306396801424002|issn=0306-3968}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 Cohen set up and co-directed the London East Research Institute (LERI), with the aim of co-ordinating the university\u2019s research on the regeneration of East London, which was gathering pace at this time and included UEL\u2019s new campus in the [[Royal Albert Dock, London|Royal Docks]]. Initially the research concentrated on the [[Thames Gateway]], the largest regeneration project in Europe at the time and this led to the publication of ''London\u2019s Turning'', a collection of studies of different aspects of the eastwards turn in London\u2019s growth.<ref>{{Cite book|title=London's turning : Thames Gateway-prospects and legacy|date=2008|publisher=Ashgate|others=Cohen, Philip, 1944-, Rustin, Michael J.|isbn=978-0-7546-7063-6|location=Aldershot, Hampshire, England|oclc=180190751}}</ref> With the announcement of London\u2019s bid for the 2012 Olympic Games and the decision to locate the main venue at Stratford, East London, the focus of LERI\u2019s work inevitably shifted to evaluating the impact on local communities of the rapid transformation of the area from industrial and residential use to hosting a world mega-event. Cohen conducted an ethnographic study of tunnellers and construction workers in the initial [https://library.olympic.org/Default/doc/SYRACUSE/41477/demolish-dig-design-the-olympic-delivery-authority-s-milestones-to-summer-2008-the-london-organising?_lg=en-GB Dig, Design and Demolish] phase and established ongoing focus groups with local residents and young people to chart their response to the unfolding impact of the Olympic project. This material formed the basis of his book \u2018''On the Wrong Side of the Track: East London and the Post Olympics?\u2019''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Philip, 1944-|title=On the wrong side of the track? : East London and the Post-Olympics|year=2013|isbn=978-1-907103-62-9|location=London|oclc=840478182}}</ref> in which Cohen explores the rhetoric and reality of the 2012 Olympic project and a follow up study features in ''London 2012 and the Post Olympic City: a hollow Legacy''? (2017).<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=London 2012 and the post-Olympics city : a hollow legacy?|others=Cohen, Philip, 1944-, Watt, Paul|date = 20 September 2017|isbn=978-1-137-48947-0|location=London|oclc=1004563490}}</ref><br />\n\n== From Urban Ethnography to Critical Cartography (2013+) ==\nCohen\u2019s approach to ethnography from the outset had a strong spatial as well as visual emphasis and he experimented with narrative mapping methods in research with young people around issues of public safety and danger. This interest was further developed with the setting up of [https://www.livingmaps.org/ Livingmaps] ,a network of artists, activists and academics to develop the theory and practice of participatory mapping in work with communities on the front line of urban regeneration. He is currently (2020) the network\u2019s research director and editor at large of its online journal, ''[http://livingmaps.review/journal/index.php/LMR/index Living Maps Review]''. The network runs a programme of public events and delivers a variety of mapping projects in partnership with schools , community organisations and local authorities. These have included ''Speaking Out of Place'' funded by the London Legacy Corporation , a participatory action research project working with residents and young people living and studying in the ex-Olympic village at Stratford East London. Outputs included a Young People\u2019s Map and Guide to the Olympic Park co-produced with students from Chobham Academy School;[https://www.livingmaps.org/completed-projects-2] a [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TfdUuj09BqE video] made with young residents exploring local issues of urban planning and an exhibition based on a community photography project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eprints.kingston.ac.uk/40415/6/Humphry-D-40415-VoR.pdf|title=SpeakingOut of Place: End of Project Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The ethnographic study of East Village was also published as a chapter in ''London 2012''.<ref name=\":5\" /> Current work includes ''The Groundbreakers,'' an audio heritage trail telling the back story of the Olympic Park and ''Young Citizens Atlas of London,'' a proposed online platform hosting material produced by a network of young 'citizen mappers' in areas of London identified in the London 2050 plan as sites of major regeneration. Plans include resources and workshops to train citizens in mapping methods to represent issues about the past, present and future of these \u2018opportunity areas\u2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KaDJF4CSXKo|title=The Citizen's Atlas (video)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><br />\n\n==Research Themes==\nCohen\u2019s academic work is trans-disciplinary and draws on concepts from [[linguistics]] and [[narratology]], [[psychoanalysis]] and [[anthropology]], [[cultural history]] and social [[Phenomenology (sociology)|phenomenology]]. Early influences were [[Basil Bernstein]]\u2019s theory of socio-linguistic codes, [[Gregory Bateson]]\u2019s model of communication and [[Mikhail Bakhtin]]\u2019s concept of [[Dialogic|dialogics]] and more recently [[Bruno Latour|Latour]]\u2019s [[Actor\u2013network theory|actor-network theory]]. In his work on social and cultural imaginaries Cohen has also drawn on both the post [[Melanie Klein|Kleinian]] and [[Lacanian]] traditions in psychoanalysis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/|title=Phil Cohen Works - Urban Ethnographer|last=Says|first=Normd|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Rethinking the youth question ==\nCohen\u2019s ground breaking analysis of youth cultures in the 1960\u2019s and 70\u2019s sought to redefine the field of youth studies, away from an empirical investigation of young people\u2019s values, attitudes and behaviour and towards a critical perspective of how \u2018youth\u2019 was being ideologically constructed and represented in policy and media discourses as a unitary social category.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|last2=Ainley|date=2000|title=In the Country of the Blind|url=|journal=Youth and Social Justice|volume=3|issue=1|pages=|via=}}</ref> He went on to consider how that was challenged or reproduced in young people's own cultural practices.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Blackman|first=Shane|title='From Here to Modernity: Rethinking the Youth Qustion with C. Wright Mills' in The Subcultural Imagination|date=2016-06-17|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-315-73068-4|location=Abingdon, Oxon ; New York, NY : Routledge, 2016. {{!}} Series|pages=|doi=10.4324/9781315730684|url=https://repository.uel.ac.uk/download/45867676a9d7c8903a6a97d90d6b89c74152c26c01033c55f6dc0cb62f70f145/668889/Gunter%20%282016%29%20From%20Bad%20to%20Worse%20final%20pre%20copy-edited%20version.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Coming of age stories ==\nCohen\u2019s recent work has focused on the narrative grammars through which life stories are constructed, and the generational shifts in way \u2018youth\u2019 is both imagined and remembered as a formative stage. This field includes an analysis of young adult fiction and contemporary films, as well as written memoirs and oral testimony, gay coming out stories and how life transitions are managed in contemporary faith communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/coming-age-stories-now/|title=Coming of age stories : now and then - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Attachment to place ==\nFrom the outset Cohen\u2019s ethnographic work has been grounded in the specificities of place, as an anchorage of symbolic or moral claims over public amenity and resource as well as a locus of collective identity and belonging. In early work he contrasted rules and rituals of territoriality with protocols of public propriety as two complimentary forms of civic stake holding.<ref>{{Citation|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Rethinking the Youth Question|chapter=Policing the Working-class City|date=1997|pages=110\u2013138|publisher=Macmillan Education UK|doi=10.1007/978-1-349-25390-6_6|isbn=978-0-333-63148-5}}</ref> In more recent work this model has been refined, drawing on the ideas of [[Michael Balint]] and [[Jay Appleton]] to outline a psychosocial geography of place attachment.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Culture and the unconscious|date=2007|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-4039-8622-1|editor-last=Bainbridge|location=|pages=|chapter=Landscape After Ruins|oclc=70673312}}</ref>\n\n== Memory politics ==\nCohen\u2019s interest in this field originated with the publication of his memoir, ''Reading Room Only'' in 2013 and has been focused on the forms of public commemoration which the Left mobilises and how this relates to the dominant apparatus of fame.<ref name=\":7\" /> In ''Archive that, Comrade'', he develops a model of archival genres and explores the forms of organisation that might be appropriate for the \u2018anarchive\u2019 that sets out to challenge or disrupt dominant knowledge power relations.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Philip, 1944- auteur.|title=Archive that, comrade! : left legacies and the counter culture of remembrance|date=June 2018|isbn=978-1-62963-506-4|oclc=1110659947}}</ref> The commemorations of the 50<sup>th</sup> anniversary of May 1968 provided an occasion for a further reflection of on the nature of political legacy and the organisation of a conference focused around that theme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/after-1968-left-legacies-and-the-politics-of-remembrance/|title=After 1968 :Left legacies and the politics of remembrance - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2018-11-01|title='1968' and the politics of memory|journal=Soundings|volume=70|issue=70|pages=8\u201321|doi=10.3898/soun.70.01.2018|issn=1362-6620}}</ref>\n\n== There goes the Labourhood ==\nOne of Cohen\u2019s major pre-occupations is the impact of de-industrialisation on working class community in Britain, especially on its cultures of masculinity and manual labour. His approach to labour history focuses on the split representation of the labouring body into Promethean and abject images, and how this in turn positions communities of labour as either backbones of the nation or a race apart. He argues that these fundamental binaries can either cut across or reinforce more familiar distinctions of occupational skill and moral status. In some of his research he has traced the evolution of these representations within specific social groups especially those who perform \u2018elemental\u2019 labour: miners, tunnellers, sweeps, mariners, foundry workers and roustabouts.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2017-08-15|title=Finding uncommon ground: working-class identity politics after Labourism|journal=Soundings|volume=66|issue=66|pages=113\u2013128|doi=10.3898/136266217821733723|issn=1362-6620}}</ref>\n\n== Unconscious racism and its other scene ==\nStarting from a critique of reductive psychologies of racism, which reduce it to patterns of prejudice, or individual pathology, Cohen looked for the social structures and cultural norms through which Freud's concept of \u2018narcissism of minor difference\u2019 might become racialised. He found these in the autochthonies which feature in myths of origin operating in discourses of nation, people , and race. Cohen argues that it is through these \u2018perversions of inheritance\u2019 that the racist imagination gains its purchase on the real and becomes 'common sense'. If the unconscious is the 'discourse of the other' (Lacan) then unconscious racism is the 'discourse of the other\u2019s discourse of the other'. Cohen argued that It follows that rationalist pedagogies favoured by anti-racists are doomed to failure since they fail to engage with the structures of disavowal which are intrinsic to racialised structures of feeling and belief.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2019-03-01|title=Both Sides of the Line: Stuart Hall and New Ethnicities, then and now|journal=New Formations|volume=96|issue=96|pages=147\u2013159|doi=10.3898/newf:96/97.06.2019|issn=0950-2378}}</ref><ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== Left fields: class, community and identity politics ==\nIn a series of articles for the journal ''Soundings''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=1997-2018|title=Various|url=|journal=Soundings: An Interdisciplinary Journal|volume=3, 50, 60, 68, 70|pages=|via=}}</ref> Cohen argued for abandoning the classic Marxist analysis of class consciousness based on the distinction between class in and for itself, and replacing it with the notion of class from and to itself, mediated by identity formations centred on multitude or tribe. Theses imagined communities of citizens have become important actors outside and sometimes against the formal apparatus of political representation, posing a direct challenge to Social Democracy. The rise of communitarianism and populism is analysed from this standpoint and a political actor network theory proposed as a way of mapping this more fluid space of ideological affiliations and affinities. These ideas are being developed further in a study examining the political culture of the British Left following the historic defeat of the Labour Party in 2019.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Left Fields: Changing Ecologies of Political Radicalism|publisher=Pluto Press|year=2020|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.compass.org|title=There Must be Some Way Out of Here: Political Mindfulness and the Left in Uncertain Times|last=Cohen|first=Phil|last2=Lister|first2=Ruth|date=2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last3=Pountain|first3=Dick|last4=Rustin|first4=Mike|authorlink4=|last5=Walkerdine|first5=Valerie}}</ref>\n\n== East London ==\nOver a forty year period some twenty projects have been carried out in different parts of East London, including the Isle of Dogs, Whitechapel, The Royal Docks, Stratford and Barking. The projects varied in scope and scale from a major comparative research project funded by the [[Economic and Social Research Council|ESRC]], to small scale community initiatives, and including local school and neighbourhood based ethnographies as well as photography, video and other visual arts projects<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/projects-map/|title=Projects Map|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (see also Filmography section below). A further study into the cultural politics of regeneration appeared in ''Regeneration Songs''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Minton|first=Anna|title='London After Shock' in Regeneration songs : sounds of investment and loss in east london|last2=Hancox|first2=Dan|last3=James|first3=Malcolm|last4=Duman|first4=Alberto|date=2018|publisher=Repeater|year=2018|isbn=978-1-912248-24-7|location=|pages=|oclc=1054344645}}</ref>\n\nAlthough not a longitudinal study in the strict sense, this long series of projects and related publications set out to capture the impact of complex structural change on the livelihoods, life styles and life stories of successive generations of young East Enders and their parents. The empirical focus was on the processes de-industrialisation, globalisation and the advent of neoliberal policies in the local housing and labour markets. Much of this work was brought together in the first part of Cohen\u2019s book about the impact of the 2012 Olympics on East London.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title='The Road to Beckton Pier' in Eastern promise : education and social renewal in London's Docklands|date=2000|publisher=Lawrence and Wishart|isbn=0-85315-898-3|editor-last=Butler|editor-first=Tim|location=|pages=|oclc=44397850}}</ref>\n\n== Intellectuals, dialogic research and the dissident academy ==\nCohen\u2019s intellectual and political formation took place outside the Academy. He does not have a first degree and he obtained a PhD by publication.<ref name=\":6\" /> He spent five years in the British Museum Reading Room following a course of independent study, and observing how some of his early ideas were taken up by academics and exploited for their own career advancement.<ref name=\":7\" /> As a result he has always been opposed to extractive forms of social research, and suspicious of the ways in which academics make intellectual capital out of the information supplied to them.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/skin-in-the-game/|title=SKIN IN THE GAME - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Instead he has experimented with alternative, non-academic ways of co-producing and disseminating research knowledge through exhibitions, films, comics and the visual arts.<ref name=\":12\" /> He has written on the curriculum of the Multicultural University,<ref>{{Citation|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=A Compact for Higher Education|chapter=What Kind Of Place Is This? Cultures of Learning, Student Identities, and the Process of Disqualification in British Higher Education 1|date=2017-11-01|pages=125\u2013138|publisher=Routledge|doi=10.4324/9781315184975-9|isbn=978-1-315-18497-5}}</ref> the historical relationship between Black and Jewish intellectuals,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/the-idea-of-the-university-in-the-age-of-the-knowledge-economy/|title=The Idea of the University and the Intellectual in the Age of the Knowledge Economy - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> the limits and conditions of dialogic/participatory research, citizen social science and the critical pedagogy of anti-racism.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/methods-in-dialogue/|title=Methods in Dialogue / Finding the Way Home - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The extent to which it is possible to sustain a culture of critical enquiry and dissent within the neo-liberal university, and in the face of toxic forms of student identity politics is considered in further studies.<ref name=\":13\" /><br />\n\n== Journalism ==\nCohen has written for numerous left wing journals, including [https://newsocialist.org.uk/ New Socialist], [[Marxism Today]], [[Soundings (journal)|Soundings]] and [[New Formations]]. He has also contributed to the online [[OpenDemocracy|Open Democracy]] platform. Since 2012 he has written a regular blog on his website on a range of topics in contemporary politics and culture.[https://philcohenworks.com/] \u00a0A collection of this material was published in 2019.<ref name=\":15\" />\n== Creative Writing : Poetry and Prose ==\nCohen began writing poetry after attending a course at the Poetry School. His poems have been published in [[Soundings (journal) - issues 2 and 6|Soundings]], [[Agenda (poetry journal) 46(2)|agenda]], [[Critical Quarterly (issue 1, 2002)|Critical Quarterly]], Metaphorica and Quartos. A collection of his poetry and prose was published in ''Graphologies'', in partnership with Jean McNeil by Mica Press in 2013.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Philip, 1944- author.|title=Graphologies|date=July 2014|isbn=978-1-869848-02-6|oclc=883870446}}</ref> \u00a0A narrative prose poem ''Postcards to Grandad'' was published in 2019.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Waypoints: toward an ecology of political mindfulness|publisher=Eyeglass Press|year=2019|isbn=978-1-9164719-6-2|location=|pages=}}</ref><br />\n\n== Filmography ==\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/the-way-we-were/ The Way \u00a0We Were Then]'' (Fragment Films 2001): A\u00a0 TV documentary\u00a0 about the \u2018hippy squat\u2019 at\u00a0144 Piccadilly, featuring an interview with \u2018Dr John\u2019.\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/tricks-of-the-trade-issues-in-multicultural-education/ Tricks of the Trade]'' (Art of Change/UEL Media Dept 1992): Made as part of an anti-racist education project with primary schools in East London and funded by the Hilden Trust. It presents the materials and includes an interview with Stuart Hall. Designed\u00a0 to accompany \u2018''Anansi meets Spiderwoman\u2019'' (BFI Education 1997).\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/empire-of-the-mind/ Empires of the Mind]''\u00a0 (Open University Film Unit 1997) This film was made to accompany the Open University Course on \u2018Race, Culture and Society\u2019 and explores the popular imagery of\u00a0 race, nation and empire that was in circulation in the Victorian school. It is introduced by Ali Rattansi.\n\n''[http://philcohenworks.com/young-east-enders-views-of-regeneration-the-north-woolwich-story/ It Ain't Our Place Any More: Young People\u2019s Views of Regeneration in East London]'' (Fundamental Architecture 2007): North Woolwich is part of the Royal Docks\u00a0 but is physically isolated by virtue of its physical\u00a0 geography and for many years was\u00a0subject to neglect by planners and politicians alike. It has a large concentration of social housing and has been home to a large, and increasingly ethnically diverse\u00a0 working class community.\u00a0 In this video young people for the area voices their hopes and fears for the future\u00a0 of the area, and consider the likely impact of\u00a0 regeneration and the Olympics.\n\n''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TfdUuj09BqE&feature=youtu.be Speaking Out of Place: Voices from East London\u2019s Olympic Legacy]'' (Aura Productions/LLDC/Livingmaps Network 2016): This film is the product of a collaboration with\u00a0 residents and young people\u00a0 in East 20. It was made as part of a larger project investigating the impact of the 2012 Olympic Legacy on local communities. The film is composed of five short segments, each examining a different aspect of the\u00a0 Olympic Legacy.\u00a0 The aim was to sample a range of local voices and opinions, and to\u00a0 raise\u00a0 wider issues about mega-event regeneration, in terms of sustainable employment, affordable housing, community development, public amenity, policing\u00a0 and youth participation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/speaking-place-reflections-londons-post-olympic-legacy/|title=SPEAKING OUT OF PLACE : reflections on London's post Olympic legacy - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/frontlines-backyards/ Front Lines, Back Yards]'' (ULIE Media Department 1988): This video presents highlights of a conference in 1987, with contributions from the main speakers including Stuart Hall, Paul Gilroy\u00a0and Phil Cohen. There are interviews with delegates, and presentations from some of the poets and artists who took part.\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/playgrounds-of-prejudice/ Playgrounds of Prejudice] (''GLC/UEL Media Productions 1985): A study of playground culture in a Dockland school, featuring a multi-perspective analysis of a fight between an Irish and Black boy. The film was made as part of the \u2018No Kidding\u2019 project funded by the GLC (1982-84).\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/methods-in-dialogue/ Methods in Dialogue]'' (ESRC/UEL Media Productions 2004): A conversation between Mike Rustin and Phil Cohen exploring the methodologies of a comparative study of class, ethnicity and gender identities amongst young people in two areas of London\u2019s docklands and two areas of Hamburg. The project was carried out in collaboration with Nora Rathzel, and funded by the ESRC and the Volkswagen Foundation.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IxVkGoZwx2M&feature=youtu.be Rethinking \u20191968\u2019]'' (Aura Productions 2018): A compilation of contributions to a conference organised as\u00a0 a Festschrift and to reflect on the legacy of \u20181968\u2019. Includes plenary contributions from Phil Cohen,\u00a0Lynne Segal, Jeremy Gilbert and Mike Rustin. \u00a0\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/lights/ Lights on for the Territory]'' (Aura Productions/Livingmaps Network 2017): A film exploring the creative and technical processes involved in making a narrative\u00a0map, focussing on a map made by John Wallett for\u00a0using a ma\n\n''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KaDJF4CSXKo&feature=youtu.be Citizens Atlas of London]\u00a0'' (Aura Productions/Livingmaps Network 2019): A film exploring the London Plan and its impact on communities living in its designated \u2018opportunity areas\u2019, featuring\u00a0contributions from Phil Cohen, Michael Edwards and Anna Minton, and the map work of Barbara Brayshay, Debbie Kent and Jina Lee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/citizens-atlas-of-london/|title=Citizens Atlas of London - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Phil}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=March 2020}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = Phil Cohen\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = PhilpicpmIMG 0219.jpg\n| image_size         = \n| alt                =\n| caption            = Cohen in 2017\n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = 1944\n| birth_place        =London \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| nationality        =British \n| citizenship        = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         =Writer and Cultural Activist \n| period             = \n| known_for          =Sociology of youth culture; impact of urban regeneration on working class culture; theories of racism and identity. Also a high profile leader of squatters rights movement in London (1960-70s). \n| home_town          =\n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             =Jean McNeil, painter \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| relatives          = \n| awards             = <!--notable national-level awards only-->\n| website            =https://philcohenworks.com/ \n| education          =St Pauls School, Cambridge University, PhD by publication \n| alma_mater         = <!--will often consist of the linked name of the last-attended higher education institution-->\n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = Basil Bernstein; Gregory Bateson; Michail Bakhtin; Bruno Latour\n| era                = \n| discipline         = Sociologist, Ethnographer\n| sub_discipline     = <!--academic discipline specialist area \u2013 e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th-century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist-->\n| workplaces         = <!--full-time positions only, not student positions-->\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Phil Cohen''' (born 1944) is a British cultural theorist, urban ethnographer, community activist, educationalist and poet. He was involved in the London underground counter culture scene and gained public notoriety as 'Dr John', a leader in the [[Squatting|squatter's rights]] movement but is now better known for his work on youth culture and the impact of urban regeneration on working class communities, particularly in East London, with a focus of issues of race and popular racism. More recently the scope of his work has widened to includes issues of identity politics, memory and loss, and the future of the Left in Britain Cohen\u2019s academic work is trans-disciplinary and draws on concepts from linguistics and narratology, psycho-analysis and anthropology, cultural history and social phenomenology. He is currently (2020) Emeritus Professor at the Centre for Cultural Studies at the University of East London, a research fellow at the Young Foundation and Research Director of the Livingmaps Network. Cohen is also a member of [[Compass (think tank)|Compass]], a [[Gramscian]] think tank within the Labour Party and is on the editorial board of [[New Formations]]. His work has been translated into French, German, Swedish, Italian, French and Japanese.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=http://philcohenworks.com/pcowwp/wp-content/uploads/PCCVjan19.final2_.pdf|title=Phil Cohen, CV|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=|website=philcohenworks.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and family==\nPhil Cohen was born into a medical family living in Bloomsbury, Central London. He was  educated at St Paul\u2019s School, London, where he studied classics and history and won a scholarship to Cambridge in 1963.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Reading Room Only|publisher=Five Leaves Publications|year=2013|isbn=978-1907869785|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.historyworkshop.org.uk/reading-room-only/|title=Reading Room Only|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2011|website=History Workshop Online|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> In 1965 Cohen dropped out of university and after a period of travelling, including work on trawlers, he became involved in the London underground counter culture scene.<ref name=\":0\" /> He subsequently became a community and youth worker in London. He was married to the late Pam Brighton, the theatre director in 1970; their son, Ned, was born the following year. He was divorced in 1978 and later married Jean McNeil, the painter in 1987. They adopted a son, Stephen, who died of an alcohol related illness in  2013 at the age of 33.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=In the best interests of the child : culture, identity, and transracial adoption|date=1994|publisher=Free Association Books|others=Gaber, Ivor., Aldridge, Jane.|isbn=1-85343-152-4|location=London|pages=|chapter=Yesterday's Words, Tomorrow's World: from the Racialisation of Adoption to the Politics of Difference|oclc=31918360}}</ref> This event is a central reference point in much of the creative writing Cohen has produced since then.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/a-tribute-in-words-and-pictures-to-ste-thomson/|title=A tribute in words and pictures to Ste Thomson|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2013|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Cohen's grandfather was a Jewish revolutionary from Vitebsk who emigrated to live in Glasgow before the First World War and was the subject of a recent prose poem.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Postcards to Grandad|publisher=Eyeglass Books|year=2019|isbn=978-1-9164719-2-4|location=|pages=}}</ref><br />\n== Youth Culture and the Alternative Society (1965 -78) ==\nWorking as an assistant to the conceptual artist [[John Latham (artist)|John Latham]], Cohen scripted \u2018happenings\u2019 with Latham and [[Jeff Nuttall]] at [[Better Books]], and was involved in the [[Wholly Communion]] Poetry Event and the [[Dialectics of Liberation Congress|Dialectics of Liberation]] conference. He also wrote for the underground paper [[International Times]]. For a time he was associated with the English [[Situationist International|Situationist]] group and its journal King Mob Echo and took an active part in several of its \u2018provocations\u2019. In 1968 he became involved in a squat at the Bell Hotel in Covent Garden out of which the [[London Street Commune]] movement emerged. Mass squats were organised in a number of prominent public buildings in Central London, culminating in the occupation of the Queen Mother\u2019s ex-residence at 144 Piccadilly in 1969 which became known as 'Hippydilly' and made world headline news.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-49607777|title=When hippy squatters took over a Piccadilly mansion|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> As one of the leaders of the movement who spoke to the media Cohen's pseudonym \u2018Dr John' featured in newsreel reports and the national press.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britishpathe.com/video/piccadilly-squatters|title=Piccadilly Squatters|last=Path\u00e9|first=British|website=www.britishpathe.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-03-03}}</ref>  British Pathe described the occupiers as 'scroungers and hell raisers' and Dr John 'the hippy squatter\u2019 briefly became an figure of fear in what he later described as a moral panic about the perceived threat that squatting posed to home ownership and private property.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/144-and-all-that-proud-archivist-event/|title=144 And All That Proud Archivist Event - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the closing down of the street commune squats, Cohen worked as a detached youth worker for the Soho Project and then set up Street Aid as a legal advice and self help organisation for homeless young people in Central London, based initially in Soho and then Covent Garden.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> In 1975/6, with a group of fellow Leftists including [[David Robins]], Cohen occupied a derelict pub near Kinds Cross and turned it into a radical cultural and education centre for local estate youth. The pub was burned down in mysterious circumstances''. Knuckle Sandwich:growing up in the working class city'' (1978) written by Cohen and Robins\u00a0gives a detailed account of the project and situates it within an analysis of urban working class youth culture.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Robins, David, 1944-2007.|title=Knuckle sandwich : growing up in the working-class city|date=1978|publisher=Penguin|others=Cohen, Philip, 1944-|isbn=0-14-021977-3|location=Harmondsworth|oclc=4958423}}</ref>\n\nThese experiences led Cohen to develop a [[Gramscian]] perspective on post war youth subcultures in Britain spelt out in a working paper published by the Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies (CCCS) in 1972 \u2018Sub-cultural Conflict and Working Class Community\u2019<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Phil.|title=Sub-cultural conflict and working class community|date=1972|publisher=Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies|oclc=809618727}}</ref> subsequently provided the basis for a CCCS book \u2018Resistance through Rituals\u2019 edited by [[Stuart Hall (cultural theorist)|Stuart Hall]] and Tony Jefferson.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Resistance through rituals : youth subcultures in post-war Britain|date=1993|publisher=Routledge|others=Hall, Stuart, 1932-2014., Jefferson, Tony.|isbn=0-415-09916-1|location=London|oclc=31183761}}</ref> The paper has since been translated into eight European languages and become something of a classic. In this text Cohen develops the notion of youth cultures as collective responses to structural shifts in class identity formation, creating distinct sets of imaginary class relations though specific codes of dress, behaviour, music and language. This analysis was initially applied to [[Mods and rockers|Mods]] and [[Skinhead|Skinheads]], in East London and subsequently to [[Beatnik|Beats]] and [[Hippie|Hippies]].<ref name=\":2\" /> In later work this initial focus on the youth question broadened to include issues of inter-generational transmission, coming of age stories and ideas surrounding different life phases.<br />\n\n== Interventions in Vocational and Anti-Racist Education (1979-1992) ==\nIn 1978 Cohen joined the Sociological Research Unit at the University of London's [[UCL Institute of Education|Institute of Education]], run by [[Basil Bernstein]] and [[Michael Young, Baron Young of Dartington|Michael Young]], carrying out two research projects funded by the [[Leverhulme Trust]] into youth cultures and changing school transitions. This led to a series of publications challenging the \u2018[[New Vocationalism|new vocationalism]]\u2018 and the [[Youth Training Scheme|youth training schemes]] then being introduced by the Conservative government under Margaret Thatcher with the aim of inculcating the values of \u2018enterprise culture\u2019.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Bates|first=Inge|title=Schooling for the dole? : the new vocationalism|date=1984|publisher=Macmillan|isbn=978-1-349-17581-9|location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire|pages=|oclc=562631949}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=1982|title=Schooling for the Dole|url=|journal=New Socialist|volume=3|pages=|via=}}</ref>\n\nMoving to the Post-16 Centre at the Institute, Cohen collaborated with the Cockpit Cultural Studies Centre to produce a series of photographic exhibitions working with early-leavers focusing on their experience of schooling and issues of working class aspiration, gender identity, and ethnicity.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|last2=Chappell|date=1983|title=Leavers and the Three 'L's|url=|journal=Schooling and Culture|volume=13|pages=|via=}}</ref> The No Kidding Project, funded by the [[Greater London Council]] (GLC) produced learning materials to support alternative, more critical forms of vocational education.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen, P.|title=Rethinking the Youth Question : Education, Labour and Cultural Studies.|date=2016|publisher=Macmillan Education, Limited|isbn=978-1-349-25390-6|location=London|pages=326+|oclc=1084386849}}</ref>\u00a0<ref>{{Citation|last=Cohen|first=Philip|title=Schooling for the Dole?|chapter=Against the New Vocationalism|date=1984|pages=104\u2013169|publisher=Macmillan Education UK|doi=10.1007/978-1-349-17581-9_4|isbn=978-0-333-36729-2}}</ref> The theoretical framework for this was developed in a number of articles.<ref>{{Citation|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Rethinking the Youth Question|chapter=Teaching Enterprise Culture: Individualism, Vocationalism and the New Right|date=1997|pages=275\u2013325|publisher=Macmillan Education UK|doi=10.1007/978-1-349-25390-6_10|isbn=978-0-333-63148-5}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|date=2014-05-12|editor-last=Ainley|editor-first=Patrick|editor2-last=Rainbird|editor2-first=Helen|title=Apprenticeship: Towards a New Paradigm of Learning|doi=10.4324/9781315042091|isbn=9781315042091}}</ref> This critical pedagogy was then further developed in the field of anti-racist education in a series of initiatives, films and teaching resources designed to offer an alternative to moral, symbolic and doctrinaire forms of anti-racism. These included:\n\n* Playgrounds of Prejudice, an ethnographic study of playground cultures in Dockland schools This was supported by a [https://philcohenworks.com/playgrounds-of-prejudice/ film] of the same title analysing a playground fight between an Irish and a Black boy.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/playgrounds-of-prejudice/|title=Playgrounds of Prejudice - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n* Ananse meets Spiderwoman, a learning resource pack for primary schools, published by the British Film Institute.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Philip, 1944-|title=Anansi meets spiderwoman : curriculum resources for tackling common-sense racism in pupil cultures|date=1994|publisher=British Film Institute|others=Haddock, Lynda., Southwark (London, England). Education Department., British Film Institute., University of East London. New Ethnicities Unit.|isbn=0-85170-433-6|location=London|oclc=30400135}}</ref>\n* [http://philcohenworks.com/pcowwp/wp-content/uploads/TRICKS-OF-THE-TRADE1.png Anansi Rap Attack]: a poster produced with the Art of Change.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/tricks-of-the-trade-issues-in-multicultural-education/|title=Tricks of the Trade - Issues in MultiCultural Education - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-04}}</ref>\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sXXk_kfAgY8 Empires of the Mind], a film produced by the Open University for the course on \u2018Race, Culture, Difference\u2019.\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_79YLaLHXyQ Tricks of the Trade]: a project film including an interview with Stuart Hall.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nThis teaching material was supported by a number of theoretical texts, including chapters in an Open University course reader<ref>{{Cite book|title=\"Race\", culture, and difference|date=1992|publisher=Sage Publications in association with the Open University|others=Donald, James, 1948-, Rattansi, Ali.|isbn=0-8039-8579-7|location=London|oclc=26052615}}</ref>, and in the Blackwell reader in Racial and Ethnic Studies.<ref>{{Cite book|title=A companion to racial and ethnic studies|date=2002|publisher=Blackwell|others=Goldberg, David Theo., Solomos, John.|isbn=0-585-46732-3|location=Malden, Mass.|oclc=53061669}}</ref>\n\nDuring this period Cohen co-edited with Angela McRobbie the Youth Questions series for Macmillan. His own books published in the series included ''Multi-Racist Britain'' (1994)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Multi-racist Britain|date=1988|publisher=Macmillan Education|others=Cohen, Philip, 1944-, Bains, Harwant S.|isbn=0-333-33249-0|location=Houndmills, Basingstoke, Hampshire|oclc=18781086}}</ref> and ''Rethinking the Youth Question: education, labour and cultural studies'' (1997)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, P.|title=Rethinking the Youth Question : Education, Labour and Cultural Studies.|date=2016|publisher=Macmillan Education, Limited|isbn=978-1-349-25390-6|oclc=1084386849}}</ref>, which brought together all his academic research on youth culture and schooling.   \n== From Race to Regeneration (1992-2012) ==\nCohen moved to the University of East London (UEL) in 1992 to set up and direct the Centre for New Ethnicities Research (CNER). The centre embarked on a programme of research and community engagement in East London around issues of popular racism and cultural identity. This included curating ''Rich Mix'' (2001), an exhibition of multicultural art in Tower Hamlets and a major conference ''Front Lines, Backyards'' (1998)<ref>{{Cite book|title=Frontlines - backyards.|date=1998|publisher=Lawrence & Wishart|isbn=0-85315-858-4|location=London|oclc=230179182}}</ref> which explored issues surrounding changing identifications people might make when confronted by when confronted by rapid social and demographic change. Research projects included ethnographic studies of frontline situations of racial conflict in East London, a funded research programme on young people\u2019s perceptions of class, gender and ethnicity in two areas of London and Hamburg whose results were published as ''Finding the Way Home'' (2004);<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite book|last=R\u00e4thzel, Nora, Hrsg. Cohen, Phil.|title=Finding the way home : young people's stories of gender, ethnicity, class, and places in Hamburg and London|date=2008|publisher=V & R Unipress|isbn=978-3-89971-433-3|oclc=246627976}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title='All White on the Night' in Rising in the East?: the regeneration of East London|last2=Rustin|first2=Mike|date=1996|publisher=Lawrence & Wishart|isbn=0-85315-844-4|editor-last=Butler|editor-first=Tim|location=|pages=|oclc=468564617}}</ref><ref name=\":10\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=1997|editor-last=Frankenberg|editor-first=Ruth|title='Labouring Under Whiteness' in Displacing Whiteness|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1215/9780822382270|isbn=978-0-8223-2011-1}}</ref> The centre organised a programme of talks and working papers, some of which was published in ''New Ethnicities, Old Racisms.''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Phil, 1944-|title=New ethnicities, old racisms?|date=1999|publisher=Zed|isbn=1-85649-651-1|oclc=464583221}}</ref> The Centre\u2019s work was influential, especially in directing attention \u00a0to the deeper, more unconscious, reaches of the popular racist imagination. However the use of psychoanalytic and anthropological concepts to understand the interplay of myth, ritual and phantasy in the construction of 'common sense' racist narratives was controversial, especially amongst Marxist critics who took this work to be symptomatic of [[false consciousness]] and an issue of ''Race and Class'' was devoted to attacking the Centre\u2019s work.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Gordon|first=Paul|date=April 2001|title=Psychoanalysis and Racism: The Politics of Defeat|journal=Race & Class|volume=42|issue=4|pages=17\u201334|doi=10.1177/0306396801424002|issn=0306-3968}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004 Cohen set up and co-directed the London East Research Institute (LERI), with the aim of co-ordinating the university\u2019s research on the regeneration of East London, which was gathering pace at this time and included UEL\u2019s new campus in the [[Royal Albert Dock, London|Royal Docks]]. Initially the research concentrated on the [[Thames Gateway]], the largest regeneration project in Europe at the time and this led to the publication of ''London\u2019s Turning'', a collection of studies of different aspects of the eastwards turn in London\u2019s growth.<ref>{{Cite book|title=London's turning : Thames Gateway-prospects and legacy|date=2008|publisher=Ashgate|others=Cohen, Philip, 1944-, Rustin, Michael J.|isbn=978-0-7546-7063-6|location=Aldershot, Hampshire, England|oclc=180190751}}</ref> With the announcement of London\u2019s bid for the 2012 Olympic Games and the decision to locate the main venue at Stratford, East London, the focus of LERI\u2019s work inevitably shifted to evaluating the impact on local communities of the rapid transformation of the area from industrial and residential use to hosting a world mega-event. Cohen conducted an ethnographic study of tunnellers and construction workers in the initial [https://library.olympic.org/Default/doc/SYRACUSE/41477/demolish-dig-design-the-olympic-delivery-authority-s-milestones-to-summer-2008-the-london-organising?_lg=en-GB Dig, Design and Demolish] phase and established ongoing focus groups with local residents and young people to chart their response to the unfolding impact of the Olympic project. This material formed the basis of his book \u2018''On the Wrong Side of the Track: East London and the Post Olympics?\u2019''<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Philip, 1944-|title=On the wrong side of the track? : East London and the Post-Olympics|year=2013|isbn=978-1-907103-62-9|location=London|oclc=840478182}}</ref> in which Cohen explores the rhetoric and reality of the 2012 Olympic project and a follow up study features in ''London 2012 and the Post Olympic City: a hollow Legacy''? (2017).<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|title=London 2012 and the post-Olympics city : a hollow legacy?|others=Cohen, Philip, 1944-, Watt, Paul|date = 20 September 2017|isbn=978-1-137-48947-0|location=London|oclc=1004563490}}</ref><br />\n\n== From Urban Ethnography to Critical Cartography (2013+) ==\nCohen\u2019s approach to ethnography from the outset had a strong spatial as well as visual emphasis and he experimented with narrative mapping methods in research with young people around issues of public safety and danger. This interest was further developed with the setting up of [https://www.livingmaps.org/ Livingmaps] ,a network of artists, activists and academics to develop the theory and practice of participatory mapping in work with communities on the front line of urban regeneration. He is currently (2020) the network\u2019s research director and editor at large of its online journal, ''[http://livingmaps.review/journal/index.php/LMR/index Living Maps Review]''. The network runs a programme of public events and delivers a variety of mapping projects in partnership with schools , community organisations and local authorities. These have included ''Speaking Out of Place'' funded by the London Legacy Corporation , a participatory action research project working with residents and young people living and studying in the ex-Olympic village at Stratford East London. Outputs included a Young People\u2019s Map and Guide to the Olympic Park co-produced with students from Chobham Academy School;[https://www.livingmaps.org/completed-projects-2] a [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TfdUuj09BqE video] made with young residents exploring local issues of urban planning and an exhibition based on a community photography project.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eprints.kingston.ac.uk/40415/6/Humphry-D-40415-VoR.pdf|title=SpeakingOut of Place: End of Project Report|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> The ethnographic study of East Village was also published as a chapter in ''London 2012''.<ref name=\":5\" /> Current work includes ''The Groundbreakers,'' an audio heritage trail telling the back story of the Olympic Park and ''Young Citizens Atlas of London,'' a proposed online platform hosting material produced by a network of young 'citizen mappers' in areas of London identified in the London 2050 plan as sites of major regeneration. Plans include resources and workshops to train citizens in mapping methods to represent issues about the past, present and future of these \u2018opportunity areas\u2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KaDJF4CSXKo|title=The Citizen's Atlas (video)|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref><br />\n\n==Research Themes==\nCohen\u2019s academic work is trans-disciplinary and draws on concepts from [[linguistics]] and [[narratology]], [[psychoanalysis]] and [[anthropology]], [[cultural history]] and social [[Phenomenology (sociology)|phenomenology]]. Early influences were [[Basil Bernstein]]\u2019s theory of socio-linguistic codes, [[Gregory Bateson]]\u2019s model of communication and [[Mikhail Bakhtin]]\u2019s concept of [[Dialogic|dialogics]] and more recently [[Bruno Latour|Latour]]\u2019s [[Actor\u2013network theory|actor-network theory]]. In his work on social and cultural imaginaries Cohen has also drawn on both the post [[Melanie Klein|Kleinian]] and [[Lacanian]] traditions in psychoanalysis.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/|title=Phil Cohen Works - Urban Ethnographer|last=Says|first=Normd|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Rethinking the youth question ==\nCohen\u2019s ground breaking analysis of youth cultures in the 1960\u2019s and 70\u2019s sought to redefine the field of youth studies, away from an empirical investigation of young people\u2019s values, attitudes and behaviour and towards a critical perspective of how \u2018youth\u2019 was being ideologically constructed and represented in policy and media discourses as a unitary social category.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|last2=Ainley|date=2000|title=In the Country of the Blind|url=|journal=Youth and Social Justice|volume=3|issue=1|pages=|via=}}</ref> He went on to consider how that was challenged or reproduced in young people's own cultural practices.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Blackman|first=Shane|title='From Here to Modernity: Rethinking the Youth Qustion with C. Wright Mills' in The Subcultural Imagination|date=2016-06-17|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-315-73068-4|location=Abingdon, Oxon ; New York, NY : Routledge, 2016. {{!}} Series|pages=|doi=10.4324/9781315730684|url=https://repository.uel.ac.uk/download/45867676a9d7c8903a6a97d90d6b89c74152c26c01033c55f6dc0cb62f70f145/668889/Gunter%20%282016%29%20From%20Bad%20to%20Worse%20final%20pre%20copy-edited%20version.pdf}}</ref>\n\n== Coming of age stories ==\nCohen\u2019s recent work has focused on the narrative grammars through which life stories are constructed, and the generational shifts in way \u2018youth\u2019 is both imagined and remembered as a formative stage. This field includes an analysis of young adult fiction and contemporary films, as well as written memoirs and oral testimony, gay coming out stories and how life transitions are managed in contemporary faith communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/coming-age-stories-now/|title=Coming of age stories : now and then - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\n== Attachment to place ==\nFrom the outset Cohen\u2019s ethnographic work has been grounded in the specificities of place, as an anchorage of symbolic or moral claims over public amenity and resource as well as a locus of collective identity and belonging. In early work he contrasted rules and rituals of territoriality with protocols of public propriety as two complimentary forms of civic stake holding.<ref>{{Citation|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Rethinking the Youth Question|chapter=Policing the Working-class City|date=1997|pages=110\u2013138|publisher=Macmillan Education UK|doi=10.1007/978-1-349-25390-6_6|isbn=978-0-333-63148-5}}</ref> In more recent work this model has been refined, drawing on the ideas of [[Michael Balint]] and [[Jay Appleton]] to outline a psychosocial geography of place attachment.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Culture and the unconscious|date=2007|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-1-4039-8622-1|editor-last=Bainbridge|location=|pages=|chapter=Landscape After Ruins|oclc=70673312}}</ref>\n\n== Memory politics ==\nCohen\u2019s interest in this field originated with the publication of his memoir, ''Reading Room Only'' in 2013 and has been focused on the forms of public commemoration which the Left mobilises and how this relates to the dominant apparatus of fame.<ref name=\":7\" /> In ''Archive that, Comrade'', he develops a model of archival genres and explores the forms of organisation that might be appropriate for the \u2018anarchive\u2019 that sets out to challenge or disrupt dominant knowledge power relations.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Philip, 1944- auteur.|title=Archive that, comrade! : left legacies and the counter culture of remembrance|date=June 2018|isbn=978-1-62963-506-4|oclc=1110659947}}</ref> The commemorations of the 50<sup>th</sup> anniversary of May 1968 provided an occasion for a further reflection of on the nature of political legacy and the organisation of a conference focused around that theme.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/after-1968-left-legacies-and-the-politics-of-remembrance/|title=After 1968 :Left legacies and the politics of remembrance - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2018-11-01|title='1968' and the politics of memory|journal=Soundings|volume=70|issue=70|pages=8\u201321|doi=10.3898/soun.70.01.2018|issn=1362-6620}}</ref>\n\n== There goes the Labourhood ==\nOne of Cohen\u2019s major pre-occupations is the impact of de-industrialisation on working class community in Britain, especially on its cultures of masculinity and manual labour. His approach to labour history focuses on the split representation of the labouring body into Promethean and abject images, and how this in turn positions communities of labour as either backbones of the nation or a race apart. He argues that these fundamental binaries can either cut across or reinforce more familiar distinctions of occupational skill and moral status. In some of his research he has traced the evolution of these representations within specific social groups especially those who perform \u2018elemental\u2019 labour: miners, tunnellers, sweeps, mariners, foundry workers and roustabouts.<ref name=\":10\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2017-08-15|title=Finding uncommon ground: working-class identity politics after Labourism|journal=Soundings|volume=66|issue=66|pages=113\u2013128|doi=10.3898/136266217821733723|issn=1362-6620}}</ref>\n\n== Unconscious racism and its other scene ==\nStarting from a critique of reductive psychologies of racism, which reduce it to patterns of prejudice, or individual pathology, Cohen looked for the social structures and cultural norms through which Freud's concept of \u2018narcissism of minor difference\u2019 might become racialised. He found these in the autochthonies which feature in myths of origin operating in discourses of nation, people , and race. Cohen argues that it is through these \u2018perversions of inheritance\u2019 that the racist imagination gains its purchase on the real and becomes 'common sense'. If the unconscious is the 'discourse of the other' (Lacan) then unconscious racism is the 'discourse of the other\u2019s discourse of the other'. Cohen argued that It follows that rationalist pedagogies favoured by anti-racists are doomed to failure since they fail to engage with the structures of disavowal which are intrinsic to racialised structures of feeling and belief.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=2019-03-01|title=Both Sides of the Line: Stuart Hall and New Ethnicities, then and now|journal=New Formations|volume=96|issue=96|pages=147\u2013159|doi=10.3898/newf:96/97.06.2019|issn=0950-2378}}</ref><ref name=\":11\" />\n\n== Left fields: class, community and identity politics ==\nIn a series of articles for the journal ''Soundings''<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Cohen|first=Phil|date=1997-2018|title=Various|url=|journal=Soundings: An Interdisciplinary Journal|volume=3, 50, 60, 68, 70|pages=|via=}}</ref> Cohen argued for abandoning the classic Marxist analysis of class consciousness based on the distinction between class in and for itself, and replacing it with the notion of class from and to itself, mediated by identity formations centred on multitude or tribe. Theses imagined communities of citizens have become important actors outside and sometimes against the formal apparatus of political representation, posing a direct challenge to Social Democracy. The rise of communitarianism and populism is analysed from this standpoint and a political actor network theory proposed as a way of mapping this more fluid space of ideological affiliations and affinities. These ideas are being developed further in a study examining the political culture of the British Left following the historic defeat of the Labour Party in 2019.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Left Fields: Changing Ecologies of Political Radicalism|publisher=Pluto Press|year=2020|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.compass.org|title=There Must be Some Way Out of Here: Political Mindfulness and the Left in Uncertain Times|last=Cohen|first=Phil|last2=Lister|first2=Ruth|date=2020|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|last3=Pountain|first3=Dick|last4=Rustin|first4=Mike|authorlink4=|last5=Walkerdine|first5=Valerie}}</ref>\n\n== East London ==\nOver a forty year period some twenty projects have been carried out in different parts of East London, including the Isle of Dogs, Whitechapel, The Royal Docks, Stratford and Barking. The projects varied in scope and scale from a major comparative research project funded by the [[Economic and Social Research Council|ESRC]], to small scale community initiatives, and including local school and neighbourhood based ethnographies as well as photography, video and other visual arts projects<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/projects-map/|title=Projects Map|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> (see also Filmography section below). A further study into the cultural politics of regeneration appeared in ''Regeneration Songs''.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Minton|first=Anna|title='London After Shock' in Regeneration songs : sounds of investment and loss in east london|last2=Hancox|first2=Dan|last3=James|first3=Malcolm|last4=Duman|first4=Alberto|date=2018|publisher=Repeater|year=2018|isbn=978-1-912248-24-7|location=|pages=|oclc=1054344645}}</ref>\n\nAlthough not a longitudinal study in the strict sense, this long series of projects and related publications set out to capture the impact of complex structural change on the livelihoods, life styles and life stories of successive generations of young East Enders and their parents. The empirical focus was on the processes de-industrialisation, globalisation and the advent of neoliberal policies in the local housing and labour markets. Much of this work was brought together in the first part of Cohen\u2019s book about the impact of the 2012 Olympics on East London.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title='The Road to Beckton Pier' in Eastern promise : education and social renewal in London's Docklands|date=2000|publisher=Lawrence and Wishart|isbn=0-85315-898-3|editor-last=Butler|editor-first=Tim|location=|pages=|oclc=44397850}}</ref>\n\n== Intellectuals, dialogic research and the dissident academy ==\nCohen\u2019s intellectual and political formation took place outside the Academy. He does not have a first degree and he obtained a PhD by publication.<ref name=\":6\" /> He spent five years in the British Museum Reading Room following a course of independent study, and observing how some of his early ideas were taken up by academics and exploited for their own career advancement.<ref name=\":7\" /> As a result he has always been opposed to extractive forms of social research, and suspicious of the ways in which academics make intellectual capital out of the information supplied to them.<ref name=\":13\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/skin-in-the-game/|title=SKIN IN THE GAME - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> Instead he has experimented with alternative, non-academic ways of co-producing and disseminating research knowledge through exhibitions, films, comics and the visual arts.<ref name=\":12\" /> He has written on the curriculum of the Multicultural University,<ref>{{Citation|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=A Compact for Higher Education|chapter=What Kind Of Place Is This? Cultures of Learning, Student Identities, and the Process of Disqualification in British Higher Education 1|date=2017-11-01|pages=125\u2013138|publisher=Routledge|doi=10.4324/9781315184975-9|isbn=978-1-315-18497-5}}</ref> the historical relationship between Black and Jewish intellectuals,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/the-idea-of-the-university-in-the-age-of-the-knowledge-economy/|title=The Idea of the University and the Intellectual in the Age of the Knowledge Economy - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> the limits and conditions of dialogic/participatory research, citizen social science and the critical pedagogy of anti-racism.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/methods-in-dialogue/|title=Methods in Dialogue / Finding the Way Home - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> The extent to which it is possible to sustain a culture of critical enquiry and dissent within the neo-liberal university, and in the face of toxic forms of student identity politics is considered in further studies.<ref name=\":13\" /><br />\n\n== Journalism ==\nCohen has written for numerous left wing journals, including [https://newsocialist.org.uk/ New Socialist], [[Marxism Today]], [[Soundings (journal)|Soundings]] and [[New Formations]]. He has also contributed to the online [[OpenDemocracy|Open Democracy]] platform. Since 2012 he has written a regular blog on his website on a range of topics in contemporary politics and culture.[https://philcohenworks.com/] \u00a0A collection of this material was published in 2019.<ref name=\":15\" />\n== Creative Writing : Poetry and Prose ==\nCohen began writing poetry after attending a course at the Poetry School. His poems have been published in [[Soundings (journal) - issues 2 and 6|Soundings]], [[Agenda (poetry journal) 46(2)|agenda]], [[Critical Quarterly (issue 1, 2002)|Critical Quarterly]], Metaphorica and Quartos. A collection of his poetry and prose was published in ''Graphologies'', in partnership with Jean McNeil by Mica Press in 2013.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Cohen, Philip, 1944- author.|title=Graphologies|date=July 2014|isbn=978-1-869848-02-6|oclc=883870446}}</ref> \u00a0A narrative prose poem ''Postcards to Grandad'' was published in 2019.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite book|last=Cohen|first=Phil|title=Waypoints: toward an ecology of political mindfulness|publisher=Eyeglass Press|year=2019|isbn=978-1-9164719-6-2|location=|pages=}}</ref><br />\n\n== Filmography ==\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/the-way-we-were/ The Way \u00a0We Were Then]'' (Fragment Films 2001): A\u00a0 TV documentary\u00a0 about the \u2018hippy squat\u2019 at\u00a0144 Piccadilly, featuring an interview with \u2018Dr John\u2019.\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/tricks-of-the-trade-issues-in-multicultural-education/ Tricks of the Trade]'' (Art of Change/UEL Media Dept 1992): Made as part of an anti-racist education project with primary schools in East London and funded by the Hilden Trust. It presents the materials and includes an interview with Stuart Hall. Designed\u00a0 to accompany \u2018''Anansi meets Spiderwoman\u2019'' (BFI Education 1997).\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/empire-of-the-mind/ Empires of the Mind]''\u00a0 (Open University Film Unit 1997) This film was made to accompany the Open University Course on \u2018Race, Culture and Society\u2019 and explores the popular imagery of\u00a0 race, nation and empire that was in circulation in the Victorian school. It is introduced by Ali Rattansi.\n\n''[http://philcohenworks.com/young-east-enders-views-of-regeneration-the-north-woolwich-story/ It Ain't Our Place Any More: Young People\u2019s Views of Regeneration in East London]'' (Fundamental Architecture 2007): North Woolwich is part of the Royal Docks\u00a0 but is physically isolated by virtue of its physical\u00a0 geography and for many years was\u00a0subject to neglect by planners and politicians alike. It has a large concentration of social housing and has been home to a large, and increasingly ethnically diverse\u00a0 working class community.\u00a0 In this video young people for the area voices their hopes and fears for the future\u00a0 of the area, and consider the likely impact of\u00a0 regeneration and the Olympics.\n\n''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TfdUuj09BqE&feature=youtu.be Speaking Out of Place: Voices from East London\u2019s Olympic Legacy]'' (Aura Productions/LLDC/Livingmaps Network 2016): This film is the product of a collaboration with\u00a0 residents and young people\u00a0 in East 20. It was made as part of a larger project investigating the impact of the 2012 Olympic Legacy on local communities. The film is composed of five short segments, each examining a different aspect of the\u00a0 Olympic Legacy.\u00a0 The aim was to sample a range of local voices and opinions, and to\u00a0 raise\u00a0 wider issues about mega-event regeneration, in terms of sustainable employment, affordable housing, community development, public amenity, policing\u00a0 and youth participation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/speaking-place-reflections-londons-post-olympic-legacy/|title=SPEAKING OUT OF PLACE : reflections on London's post Olympic legacy - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref> \u00a0 \u00a0 \u00a0 \n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/frontlines-backyards/ Front Lines, Back Yards]'' (ULIE Media Department 1988): This video presents highlights of a conference in 1987, with contributions from the main speakers including Stuart Hall, Paul Gilroy\u00a0and Phil Cohen. There are interviews with delegates, and presentations from some of the poets and artists who took part.\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/playgrounds-of-prejudice/ Playgrounds of Prejudice] (''GLC/UEL Media Productions 1985): A study of playground culture in a Dockland school, featuring a multi-perspective analysis of a fight between an Irish and Black boy. The film was made as part of the \u2018No Kidding\u2019 project funded by the GLC (1982-84).\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/methods-in-dialogue/ Methods in Dialogue]'' (ESRC/UEL Media Productions 2004): A conversation between Mike Rustin and Phil Cohen exploring the methodologies of a comparative study of class, ethnicity and gender identities amongst young people in two areas of London\u2019s docklands and two areas of Hamburg. The project was carried out in collaboration with Nora Rathzel, and funded by the ESRC and the Volkswagen Foundation.<ref name=\":14\" />\n\n''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IxVkGoZwx2M&feature=youtu.be Rethinking \u20191968\u2019]'' (Aura Productions 2018): A compilation of contributions to a conference organised as\u00a0 a Festschrift and to reflect on the legacy of \u20181968\u2019. Includes plenary contributions from Phil Cohen,\u00a0Lynne Segal, Jeremy Gilbert and Mike Rustin. \u00a0\n\n''[https://philcohenworks.com/lights/ Lights on for the Territory]'' (Aura Productions/Livingmaps Network 2017): A film exploring the creative and technical processes involved in making a narrative\u00a0map, focussing on a map made by John Wallett for\u00a0using a ma\n\n''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KaDJF4CSXKo&feature=youtu.be Citizens Atlas of London]\u00a0'' (Aura Productions/Livingmaps Network 2019): A film exploring the London Plan and its impact on communities living in its designated \u2018opportunity areas\u2019, featuring\u00a0contributions from Phil Cohen, Michael Edwards and Anna Minton, and the map work of Barbara Brayshay, Debbie Kent and Jina Lee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://philcohenworks.com/citizens-atlas-of-london/|title=Citizens Atlas of London - Phil Cohen Works|language=en|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cohen, Phil}}\n[[Category:1943 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{Improve categories|date=March 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Tobybutler", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phil_Cohen_(cultural_theorist_and_ethnographer)"}
